- The 1855 Classification of the Great Growths of the Gironde

Only the wines of the Médoc were classified, with the exception of Haut-Brion from Graves. The other fine red- wine-producing districts of Saint Emilion, Pomerol and Graves were overlooked with the result that for more than one hundred years the wines from these districts suffered unfairly in prestige and reputation. In addition to the five classified growths, seven wines were unofficially considered as “crus exceptionnels” and hundreds of minor chateaux were unofficially listed but not officially classified as “crus bourgeois” and “crus artisans.”

In the new classification, the author has upgraded certain

_ deserving “crus exceptionnels” und a few “crus bourgeois” not included in the official classification, as well as the chateaux of Saint Emilion, Pomerol and Graves, which today are producing distinguished wines recognized for their quality and prestige, as well as by the high prices paid.
